Sure! Below is an example of how to generate a table of contents (TOC) automatically in a LaTeX document. This example includes the necessary commands to ensure that the TOC is updated every time the document is compiled.

Here's the step-by-step guide and the corresponding LaTeX code:

### Step-by-Step Guide

1. **Open a LaTeX Document**: Start by opening your LaTeX editor and creating a new document.

2. **Include the `hyperref` Package (Optional but Recommended)**:
   - This package makes the table of contents items clickable and easier to navigate.
   ```latex
   \usepackage{hyperref}
   ```

3. **Add the Table of Contents Command in the Document Body**:
   - Use the `\tableofcontents` command to generate the TOC.
   ```latex
   \begin{document}
   \tableofcontents
   ```

4. **Create Sections and Subsections**:
   - Add sections and subsections that will appear in the TOC.
   ```latex
   \section{Introduction}
   This is the introduction section.

   \section{Background}
   This is the background section.

   \subsection{History}
   This subsection is under the background section.

   \section{Methodology}
   This is the methodology section.

   \subsection{Data Collection}
   This subsection is under the methodology section.

   \subsection{Data Analysis}
   This subsection is under the methodology section.
   ```

5. **End the Document**:
   - Ensure that the document ends properly.
   ```latex
   \end{document}
   ```

### Full Example

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{hyperref}

\begin{document}

\tableofcontents

\section{Introduction}
This is the introduction section.

\section{Background}
This is the background section.

\subsection{History}
This subsection is under the background section.

\section{Methodology}
This is the methodology section.

\subsection{Data Collection}
This subsection is under the methodology section.

\subsection{Data Analysis}
This subsection is under the methodology section.

\end{document}
```

### Explanation

1. **`\documentclass{article}`**: Defines the document class as `article`.
2. **`\usepackage{hyperref}`**: Includes the `hyperref` package for clickable TOC entries.
3. **`\begin{document}` and `\end{document}`**: Marks the beginning and end of the document content.
4. **`\tableofcontents`**: The command that generates the TOC.
5. **`\section` and `\subsection`**: Commands to define sections and subsections, which will be included in the TOC.

When you compile this LaTeX document, it will generate a table of contents at the beginning of the document, listing all the sections and subsections.

To draw a chessboard to show a specific state of a chess game using LaTeX, you will need to use the `chessboard` package. Below is an example of how to do this:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{chessboard}

\begin{document}

\begin{center}
\newgame % Creates an empty board
\fenboard{rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR} % FEN notation of an empty board
\chessboard[setfen=rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR] % FEN notation of a specific state of the chess game
\end{center}

\end{document}
```

Here, the `\newgame` command creates an empty board. The `\fenboard{}` command is used to set up the board according to the FEN notation provided. The `setfen` option in `\chessboard` will then draw the board according to the provided FEN notation, which represents a specific state of a chess game.

Please make sure to include the `chessboard` package in your LaTeX document before using the commands above. If you are using an editor like Overleaf, you can add the package by including the line `\usepackage{chessboard}` at the beginning of your document.

